@article{Smith2014,
abstract = {The value of mechanistic ecosystem modelling has long been appreciated, and in con-nection with trait-based approaches it has recently stimulated a more process-based understanding of adaptive capacities and trade-offs. Notwithstanding recent advances, even sophisticated state-of-the-art models of plankton ecosystems, some of which include hundreds of idealized species, do not accurately represent the great biodiver-sity of plankton, or the associated flexible adaptive response of plankton communities. We build on previous reviews to suggest that it may be necessary to discard some common assumptions and try new approaches in order to construct models that can make new and testable predictions about the " adaptive capacity " of plankton ecosys-tems. Major challenges remain unresolved for modelling interacting communities of producers and consumers. Rather than the common approach of mixing and match-ing existing model components, each laden with its own legacy assumptions, we suggest that a judicious combination of innovative, mechanistic approaches that combine traits and trade-offs will likely better address such challenges. If we are to understand the potential impacts of climate change, or other environmental changes, on marine eco-systems and the biogeochemical cycles that they mediate, we need plankton ecosystem models that can represent realistically the adaptive response of diverse communities. A previous " Horizons " article (Franks, 2009) addressed the " Perplexing parameterizations and a failure to fail " in planktonic ecosystem modelling and suggested the need to develop models that scale from the adaptive response of individual organisms to the community response of ecosys-tems. Building on these suggestions, and on more recent reviews of advances in trait-based (Follows and Dutkiewicz, 2011) and optimality-based (Smith et al., 2011) modelling, we address more specifically the need to break free from assumptions and approaches that hinder the ability to model the adaptive response and biodiversity of plankton ecosystems. We intend to encourage innov-ation of new interpretations for observations and new model formulations, even though this may, often incorrect-ly, be considered more risky (and more difficult to publish) than straightforward application of the " well accepted " . Traits and the trade-offs among them play central roles in modelling the adaptive response of planktonic ecosys-tems (Follows and Dutkiewicz, 2011; Smith et al., 2011). Traits, which define the response of each species to envir-onmental conditions (Fig. 1), are the result of evolution by natural selection, operating subject to constraints, which are broadly termed trade-offs. The distribution of traits within a community defines its functional biodiversity and adaptive capacity. Therefore, it is crucial that traits and trade-offs are identified and quantified accurately. In this context, we first briefly discuss the legacy as-sumption of Michaelis– Menten kinetics for nutrient uptake by phytoplankton and how it led recently to the mis-identification of a putative trade-off for nutrient uptake. Then we address the legacy assumption of strong diffusive limitation of phytoplankton at low nutrient con-centrations. Next, we discuss more recent and promising developments that have advanced our understanding by accounting explicitly for the size-scaling of nutrient uptake traits in theoretical models. As a final example we discuss a legacy assumption about the cost of foraging by zooplankton in terms of energy dissipation in the sur-rounding water. Common to all these examples is the change in perspective that we gain by combining trait-based approaches with the fundamental principles of optimal resource allocation subject to trade-offs. Lastly, we elaborate on some ideas intended to foster progress in modelling the adaptive capacity of plankton ecosystems.},
